title: NZ Covid Data Exploration Pt 1
description: A look at the covid datasets produced by NZ.
contents:
NZ Covid Case data exploration
With the recent spike in cases in NZ, and interest in the new Variant BA.5, It would be interesting to look at case numbers by age group.
Cases in younger age groups remain low relative to previous peak form the initial opening up wave.



Cases in older age groups are climbing fast and above previous peak levels.



So far there is no evidence of widespread re-infections
However for 20-29 age group. Reinfections are on the rise. Mostly after a period of 90 days.

title: NSW Case Ascertainment
description: Using the apyramid package to compare how Covid-19 cases are discovered by age group
contents:
NSW Case data
1. NSW cases in the past 2 weeks
Looking at case data for the past 2 weeks, a large portion are in the 0-19 age group. However, the 70+ age group, which is the main user of PCR tests, also had a significant number of cases


NSWc <- NSW %>%
  filter(notification_date >= '2022-06-12') %>% 
  group_by(age_group, confirmed_by_pcr) %>% 
  summarise(PCR = sum(confirmed_cases_count))


age_pyramid(data = NSWc, age_group = 'age_group',
            split_by = 'confirmed_by_pcr', count = 'PCR')




2. NSW cases since RAT tests became available
Looking back to the start of Rapid Antigen Tests (RAT) being sold in NSW, we can see the pattern has been roughly that same. A large amount of the cases are aged 0-19 years old and the point where PCR becomes the main test type is around age 50 and over.



Data can be access from NSW COVID-19 cases by age range

title: Queensland Covid Cases in 2022
description: A look at the daily covid case counts in Qld so far in 2022.
contents:
Covid case data by 5 year cohort is found at the Qld data portal Qld Data Portal.
The data is imported as a csv file with the notifcation date of the case as well as the 5 year age bracket the case falls into.

# A tibble: 582,926 x 2
   NOTIFICATION_DATE AGE_GROUP_5Y
   <date>            <fct>       
 1 2020-01-28        40-44 years 
 2 2020-01-30        40-44 years 
 3 2020-02-04        05-09 years 
 4 2020-02-04        35-39 years 
 5 2020-02-06        35-39 years 
 6 2020-02-22        55-59 years 
 7 2020-02-22        50-54 years 
 8 2020-02-24        55-59 years 
 9 2020-02-28        60-64 years 
10 2020-03-02        20-24 years 
# ... with 582,916 more rows

The date is imported as a character and was converted using as.Date(). Also the Age Groups were converted to a factor for easier grouping.
The next step is to filter data since 1st of December in 2021 which was when the border was opened, and local cases were allowed to grow.


qld2 <- qld %>%
  filter(NOTIFICATION_DATE > '2021-12-01') %>%
  filter(AGE_GROUP_5Y != '100+ years') %>%
  filter(!is.na(AGE_GROUP_5Y)) %>% 
  group_by(NOTIFICATION_DATE) %>% 
  count(AGE_GROUP_5Y)



removed the plots for NA and 100+ age groups
